content: hello dear students! I am Ando, I am your teacher today.

Last week, you learned this 12th move, am I correct?
what was the conclusion about this move? who can tell?
no idea yet, that is my first theory lesson
I wasn't on lesson, but I think white is comfortable
i need many luck vs Ando
hehe ,MR.yyfcsd showed us this 13 last SAT.
i dont want fight with Mr RT and TUNNET in The 3rd ORC Online Tournament,they are too strong for us(Mr SamSite strong too)
mabye I am the strongest of the  world~
but this come ture mabye after 20 years~`
if you play white, of course not...
you need to learn hard after each lesson,
the study time is not just 90 minutes on saturday,
if you learn in lesson "it is black little better",
but you dont know why and where better,
so, i hope you can be more strict to yourself
today we will learn about the "old" 12th move.
After the end of lesson, i hope you all review what you learned,
and try to make everything clear,
while it is still fresh in your memories
This 12th move has always been popular throughout the years.
you have seen it being played even among top players
Let me begin with a question
is it better for black or white?
from your answers, i can see its not very obvious position
it is not easy to tell whether it is better for black or white
that with proper knowledge, white is always little better here
but if we dont know variants well,
this 14 is one of the two popular 14th moves.
I have been white here in serious games, and also black
i remember being black against Sagara in 1999, and Nikonov 2001
and i was lucky to win both games
yboil wait a moment, we will get there soon
amazingly, black position had faded so soon
when i played these moves, i was hoping for i5 development
looked like a nice space attack
if i had played 23-i5, i would have lost the game so fast.
I saw the cut coming, so I changed the 23rd move.
finally, i won the game in the end,
because he played some uncertain moves.
but to be honest, white stand better here
two years later, in 2001, i tried this variant against Nikonov,
but he surprised me with another 16th move.
It seemed a very arrogant move,
there are two main branches for black here
superak suggested a rather unusual move, to g5,
how many of you have seen it before?
white seems cant V at right
so, if such move happened in real game, i would need to find the plan for white.
how do we find the white next move,
it is a procedure of thinking
first, can we win directly by VCT?
findfind, what do your answers mean?
you seem to type them by random
3. we know we need to defend
which is the most useful for ourselves
which 18th move is most useful defense?
the first thought in your mind should be j6
if it fails, only then think of other moves
and start with most hopeful defense moves
I am sorry , some problem with my virtual classroom
so next step is, does white have vct?
did anyone of you find other ways of win?
or did all find the same win? :)
not me,the one said 18-j6 is good
this move has been quite popular too
anyone wants to try whites here?
what is your idea with this 22? can you explain to others?
we play every move with idea, not by copying, right?
as long as you learn a move from somewhere, and copy it, without understanding it, then you didnt realy learn anything
if you want to become a master,
you need to learn to understand the moves
the ider maybe just for win,
it kiks me out , did i miss the check ? :P
if you dont ask why 22 there
I like this move.. :) because white have good power..
then its very hard to grasp the whole situation
here, the question is not about white power,
the question was how to survive
in many other 22nd move, black would win
so, it is actually a needed defense move
and the reason how it defends is,
it is most active move that defends the black win ?
so black will not have diagonal connection to d8
and at the same time if black attacks to e7,
and then white has VCF on right
sorry.. my english is very poor. expression is not good.. :(
so, j7 has many defense ideas in it
because, it is impossible to play 22-j7 without understanding it
and suppose somebody make a mistake there in analysis,
but everybody still copies the move,
the reason is, they didnt bother to "understand" the move, they just copied.
I remember, in many cases, i played a game with a strong master,
and soon everybody used that move
even though after game i realized my move was bad
but all other still copied my move, because they though "ando's move" must be good
and they didnt bother to check, if it is realy good or not
actually, i make mistakes too, as you all
the only way you can be world's best is,
if you learn from everybody, but trust only yourself
meaning, you collect information, but then confirm and understand, too
but Mr RT make mistaks less than us  :P
and never study if data is correct or not
most of you have lib files with thousands of variants, without knowing the meaning of them
most of you have great talent to be in the top of the world
all you need is, to understand every move you make
even it has been played by others 100000 times
because, a serious attitude can lead to new moves
can you explain this move, hobbang?
i often move unmeaning moves,so i still weak now
did you check al black moves?
what i see is that you dont understand your defense idea
before someone chooses a bravest move 26-j5,
he must be sooo sure of every detail here
but you defend by feeling here
if you checked everything before move 26
if you just copy such move from a strong player,
hoping that the strong player has a "reason" to play it,
it will not make you a strong player.
so the thinking in renju is,
trying to make the best of it

mabye it is a case that we can get a lot of knowlege  from RT's lesson beside about renju
i can teach you many things,
but dont take it for granted
so every time you learn something from me,
please study it by yourself too
to find the bugs in my theory, weaknesses, etc
only then you will be super strong!
if you just learn this lesson amount,
yes, i always study this way
and trying to find bugs there
trying to understand every diagram of the book
it has given me an impression that white is realy doing well here.
white doesn't even need another 14th move.
you can temporarily agree now. And fully agree later, after having done your own confirmation analysis :)))
however, these situations are not complicated,
you are all good enough players here,
to be able to find your way as white here.
I cannot really recommend these variants for black.
As you know, in old times, everybody played  14 here.
this cheating 15th move was hot during 2001 WC
but then after the 16th move, the variant faded
there are no good ideas left.
means, it turned out to be very bad for black eventually
but some people still gambled with it later,
now you have learned two 12th moves.
It is up to you to decide, whether you like e8 or k9.
you can enjoy both of them as you like.
Now, we will end the lesson. Thank you all for coming here. It was my pleasure to teach you tonight. All the best! Don't forget to review everything we learned!!!
